Hi Nichelle,

Congrats on getting to the next interview! This interview will be a video interview conducted through zoom. Below are some suggestions of where to prepare/practice if needed! Let me know if you would like to chat on the phone beforehand if you have any questions.

You can use the language you feel most confident using, but Python is always a good choice. Do timed coding challenges like LeetCode.com and HackerRank.com 
Leetcode - do some of the medium and hard challenge questions.

Things to remember for this interview as well as for the remaining coding interviews in the process are:

Ask clarifying questions when the problem is posed to you and ensure that you understand the required output before beginning your solution. It's often difficult to recover if you don't understand the problem entirely.
Talk through your thought process. Understanding how you approach and tackle a problem is just as important as the actual solution itself. The engineer is there to help you solve the problem, not give you an exam. Collaborative nature is a big thing we look for in our candidates so be receptive to discussion, suggestions, and hints.
Ideally, you want the end result of your code to be production quality. Short of that though, don't spend all of your time thinking about the perfect solution. If you can implement a naive solution and refine it as you go, this will be valuable to your candidacy as well.
Know your data structures & algorithms. Search trees, hash maps, linked list, etc are valuable structures to be able to build from scratch during interviews. Be prepared to answer questions about runtime and memory complexity. Often times when asked, these are hints at the best solution to the problem.
Remember your corner and edge cases, Scale is a large part of the thought process that goes into all of our products here at Indeed so thinking about the limits as we build products is extremely important.
